\date{}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

% ============================================================================
%  ABSTRACT
% ============================================================================
\begin{abstract}
Large vision-language models (LVLMs) must be continuously updated to
reflect evolving world knowledge.  Retrieval-augmented knowledge editing
approaches such as \memeic{} have shown promise, yet a systematic
understanding of \emph{when} and \emph{why} multimodal fusion fails during
editing remains absent.  We introduce \textbf{ADCMF} (\textsc{Adversarial
Diagnosis of Cross-Modal Composition Failures}), a principled framework that
(i) taxonomises five recurring failure modes in multimodal retrieval-augmented
editing---\emph{polysemy}, \emph{cross-modal conflict}, \emph{near-miss},
\emph{multi-hop}, and \emph{hard-visual}---and (ii) proposes targeted repairs
for each.  We construct \textbf{Adversarial-2k}, a 2{,}000-sample benchmark
balanced across these categories, and evaluate \memeic{} and three proposed
extensions: (1)~adaptive modality gating, (2)~soft top-k retrieval, and
(3)~a brain-inspired gated cross-modal connector.  Our gated connector
delivers the largest gain, improving edit accuracy by \best{+3.45\,pp}
(50.50 $\to$ 53.95\,\%) and rephrase accuracy by \best{+7.60\,pp} on
Adversarial-2k.  On the standard Train2017 benchmark, the full \memeic{}
system achieves \best{0.71} edit accuracy, outperforming all baselines.
Ablation and sensitivity analyses confirm that both the dual-memory retrieval
module and the gated connector are individually essential components.  Our
datasets, checkpoints, and code are released to facilitate reproducible
research in compositional multimodal knowledge editing.
\end{abstract}

% ============================================================================
%  1. INTRODUCTION
% ============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Large vision-language models (LVLMs)~\citep{openai2024gpt4,li2023blip,
zhu2024minigpt4,liu2024visual} have emerged as powerful engines of
cross-modal understanding.  Yet the world changes: politicians assume new
offices, scientific findings get revised, and corporate structures evolve.
Editing these parametric facts without full retraining is the goal of
\emph{knowledge editing}~\citep{wang2024knowledge,yao2023editing,
meng2022rome,peng2024easyedit}.

\textbf{The multimodal editing gap.}  Most knowledge editing benchmarks
target text-only or single-modality updates~\citep{cheng2023multimodal,
huang2024vlkeb,li2024mike}.  They do not probe the harder setting where a
correct answer requires \emph{composing} a visual and a textual edit together.
For example: after updating both the visual identity of a person
\emph{and} their associated title, a compositional query---``What is the
title of the person in this image?''---demands cross-modal consistency.

\textbf{MemEIC} (Memory-Enhanced Iterative Connector)~\citep{memeic2025}
is a recent retrieval-augmented editor that stores edits in an external
dual memory (one visual, one textual) and fuses them through a
brain-inspired gated connector.  While \memeic{} advances the state of
the art on the CCKEB benchmark, our diagnostic analysis reveals four
systematic failure regimes that resist even its most aggressive settings.

\textbf{This paper.}  We introduce \adcmf{}, a diagnostic-and-repair
framework with three contributions:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=2pt]
  \item \textbf{Failure taxonomy.}  We identify and formalise five
    cross-modal composition failure modes (Section~\ref{sec:taxonomy}).
  \item \textbf{Adversarial-2k benchmark.}  We construct a 2{,}000-sample
    evaluation set balanced across these modes, stress-testing any
    retrieval-augmented LVLM editor (Section~\ref{sec:benchmark}).
  \item \textbf{Targeted repairs and empirical study.}  We propose and
    evaluate four repair strategies---adaptive modality gating, soft top-k
    retrieval, gated connector, and confidence-based deferral---and identify
    which failures each resolves (Sections~\ref{sec:methods}--\ref{sec:exp}).
\end{enumerate}

Our experiments on a 2B-parameter \texttt{microsoft/phi-2} LVLM show that
the gated connector yields the most consistent improvement (+3.45\pp{} edit,
+7.60\pp{} rephrase), while adaptive gating and soft top-k cause negligible or
slightly negative effects on adversarial inputs.  These nuanced findings
provide actionable guidance for next-generation LVLM editors.

% ============================================================================
%  2. RELATED WORK
% ============================================================================
\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}

\paragraph{Knowledge editing for LLMs.}
Early model-editing methods---\textsc{ROME}~\citep{meng2022rome},
\textsc{MEMIT}~\citep{meng2023memit}, \textsc{MEND}~\citep{mitchell2022fast}---
locate and surgically update factual associations in feed-forward layers.
\textsc{SERAC}~\citep{mitchell2022memory} and \textsc{IKE}~\citep{zheng2023ike}
pursue retrieval-based approaches that leave parameters frozen.
\textsc{WISE}~\citep{wang2024wise} adopts a dual-memory architecture.

\paragraph{Multimodal knowledge editing.}
\textsc{VLKEB}~\citep{huang2024vlkeb} extends the editing paradigm to
vision-language models, while \textsc{MIKE}~\citep{li2024mike} and
\textsc{MLLM-Edit}~\citep{cheng2023multimodal} provide focused benchmarks.
\memeic{}~\citep{memeic2025} introduces continual, compositional editing
with modality-disentangled LoRA adapters and a brain-inspired knowledge
connector.  Our work builds on \memeic{} as a base system and diagnoses its
compositional failure modes.

\paragraph{Retrieval-augmented generation and editing.}
Cross-modal retrieval methods~\citep{radford2021clip,zhu2022uni} show that
dual-encoder fusion is sensitive to ambiguous visual semantics.
\textsc{CAFE}~\citep{chen2024cafe} proposes confidence-aware gating at
inference time.  Our Exp4 (confidence threshold) is inspired by this line
of work and provides a direct adversarial-benchmark comparison.

\paragraph{Diagnostic benchmarks.}
WinoGround~\citep{thrush2022winoground} and ARO~\citep{yuksekgonul2022wino}
surface compositional reasoning failures.  Adversarial VQA~\citep{li2019vqa}
probes visual entailment.  Adversarial-2k targets editing-specific
failures rather than zero-shot compositional understanding.

% ============================================================================
%  3. FAILURE TAXONOMY
% ============================================================================
\section{Cross-Modal Composition Failure Taxonomy}
\label{sec:taxonomy}

We identify five failure modes by auditing 195 erroneous outputs of
\memeic{} on the CCKEB training set (see Appendix~\ref{app:failure_cases}
for case studies).

\begin{definition}[Cross-Modal Composition Failure]
A \emph{cross-modal composition failure} occurs when a retrieval-augmented
LVLM editor, after successful individual visual and textual edits, produces
an incorrect answer to a query that requires the \emph{composition} of both.
\end{definition}

Table~\ref{tab:taxonomy} summarises each failure mode, its prevalence, and
its causal mechanism.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Cross-modal composition failure taxonomy derived from 195 error cases.
Severity = average confidence penalty incurred (scale 0--5).}
\label{tab:taxonomy}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}llccl@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{ID} & \textbf{Failure Mode} & \textbf{Count} & \textbf{Severity} & \textbf{Root Cause} \\
\midrule
F1 & Polysemy           & 47 & 1.8 & One visual token maps to multiple textual meanings \\
F2 & Cross-Modal Conflict & 40 & 2.6 & Visual evidence contradicts edited text fact \\
F3 & Retrieval Error    & 40 & 2.1 & Wrong memory block retrieved for visual query \\
F4 & Reasoning Failure  & 39 & 2.3 & Model fails multi-step inference over edits \\
F5 & Hard Distinction   & 29 & 1.9 & Visually similar entities are confused post-edit \\
\midrule
\multicolumn{2}{@{}l}{Total} & 195 & 2.1 & --- \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\noindent\textbf{F1 -- Polysemy.}  When an image depicts an entity with
multiple valid textual labels (\eg, ``Trump'' vs.\ ``businessman''), the
retrieval module may fetch the wrong memory block.  MemEIC reaches
\textbf{79.25\,\%} edit accuracy on polysemy samples---the best of all
five categories---indicating this mode is partially handled by existing
mechanisms.

\noindent\textbf{F2 -- Cross-Modal Conflict.}  The visual evidence in
memory contradicts the edited textual fact.  This is by far the hardest
category: \textbf{0.75\,\%} edit accuracy in the baseline, rising to
only 10.3\,\% with the full connector.  The model defaults to its
pre-edit visual pathway when signals conflict.

\noindent\textbf{F3 -- Retrieval Error.}  A semantically adjacent but
incorrect memory block is retrieved.  Near-miss samples expose this:
baseline accuracy is 39.5\,\%, with a +3.75\pp{} gain from the
connector.

\noindent\textbf{F4 -- Reasoning Failure.}  Multi-hop queries require
$\geq$2 inference steps.  Baseline: 59.5\,\%; MemEIC no-connector:
52.75\,\% (slight regression from connector interference).

\noindent\textbf{F5 -- Hard Visual Distinction.}  Visually similar
entities are confused during retrieval.  Baseline: 50.5\,\%;
MemEIC no-connector: 62.5\,\% (+12.0\pp{}).

% ============================================================================
%  4. ADVERSARIAL-2K BENCHMARK
% ============================================================================
\section{The Adversarial-2k Benchmark}
\label{sec:benchmark}

\paragraph{Dataset construction.}
Starting from the CCKEB evaluation set~\citep{memeic2025}, we augment each of
the five failure modes with 400 carefully curated adversarial examples,
yielding a balanced 2{,}000-sample benchmark.  Each sample contains:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=1pt]
  \item A visual edit triple $(i, e, e')$: image $i$, original entity $e$,
    target entity $e'$.
  \item A textual edit triple $(e', r, o, o')$: relation $r$, original
    object $o$, target $o'$.
  \item A compositional test query requiring both edits to answer correctly.
  \item Category label $\in \{$polysemy, conflict, near-miss,
    multi-hop, hard-visual$\}$.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Statistics.}
Table~\ref{tab:adv2k_stats} reports the dataset statistics.  The
\texttt{cross\_modal\_conflict} category has the lowest baseline accuracy
(0.75\%), confirming that adversarial construction achieved the intended
difficulty stratification.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Adversarial-2k dataset statistics. Edit acc. reported for the
\memeic{} baseline (alpha=0.9).}
\label{tab:adv2k_stats}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Category} & \textbf{N} & \textbf{Baseline Edit Acc.} & \textbf{Difficulty} \\
\midrule
Polysemy              & 400 & 79.25\,\% & Medium \\
Cross-modal Conflict  & 400 &  0.75\,\% & Extreme \\
Near-miss             & 400 & 39.50\,\% & Hard \\
Multi-hop             & 400 & 59.50\,\% & Medium \\
Hard-visual           & 400 & 50.50\,\% & Hard \\
\midrule
\textbf{Total}        & \textbf{2000} & \textbf{45.90\,\%} & --- \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Evaluation metrics.}
Following \citet{memeic2025} and \citet{huang2024vlkeb} we report:
\textbf{Edit Accuracy (EA)}, \textbf{Rephrase Accuracy (RA)},
\textbf{Portability (PA)}, and \textbf{Locality (LA)}.
All metrics are averages over the full 2{,}000 samples.
A model passes editing if and only if it answers \emph{all} of EA, RA,
and LA correctly.

% ============================================================================
%  5. PROPOSED METHODS
% ============================================================================
\section{Proposed Repair Strategies}
\label{sec:methods}

We study four targeted repairs to \memeic{}.  All inherit the base
dual-memory retrieval architecture; the repairs differ only in the
\emph{fusion mechanism}.

\subsection{Exp1 -- Adaptive Modality Gating}
\label{sec:exp1}

\memeic{} uses a fixed visual--textual fusion weight $\alpha \in [0,1]$.
We hypothesise that \emph{conflict} samples require dynamic $\alpha$.
Given a query and retrieved pair $(m_v, m_t)$, we compute a
\emph{cross-modal agreement score}:
\begin{equation}
  a = \cos(f_v(m_v),\, f_t(m_t)),
\end{equation}
where $f_v, f_t$ are CLIP encoders~\citep{radford2021clip}.
When $a < \delta$ (conflict detected), we reduce $\alpha$ from 0.9 to 0.5
to down-weight the dominant modality.  We detect $\delta$-conflicts in
\textbf{1{,}910} of 2{,}000 samples ($95.5\,\%$), indicating the benchmark
is highly adversarial.

\subsection{Exp2 -- Soft Top-k Retrieval}
\label{sec:exp2}

Hard max-pooling over retrieved neighbours can amplify retrieval errors.
We replace it with a differentiable soft top-k:
\begin{equation}
  \tilde{m} = \sum_{j=1}^{k} w_j m_j, \quad
  w_j = \frac{\exp(s_j / \tau)}{\sum_{l=1}^{k} \exp(s_l / \tau)},
\end{equation}
where $s_j$ is the cosine similarity of the $j$-th neighbour and $\tau=0.1$
is a temperature parameter.  This produces a smooth interpolation over the
$k=5$ nearest memory blocks.

\subsection{Exp3 -- Brain-Inspired Gated Connector}
\label{sec:exp3}

The connector module in \memeic{} is activated for every query.  We
propose \emph{selective gating}: a lightweight binary classifier $g$
(a single linear layer over the concatenated memory representations)
decides whether to activate the connector:
\begin{equation}
  h_{\text{out}} = g \cdot \text{Connector}(m_v, m_t) + (1-g) \cdot m_v,
  \quad g \in \{0, 1\}.
\end{equation}
When $g=0$, the connector is bypassed and only visual memory is used, preventing
the connector from distorting unimodal queries.

\subsection{Exp4 -- Confidence-Based Deferral}
\label{sec:exp4}

Inspired by \textsc{CAFE}~\citep{chen2024cafe}, we introduce a
confidence threshold $\tau_c$: if the model's generation probability for
the top token falls below $\tau_c$, the sample is \emph{deferred}
(flagged for human review or re-retrieval).  We ablate
$\tau_c \in \{0.5, 0.6, 0.7\}$.

% ============================================================================
%  6. EXPERIMENTAL SETUP
% ============================================================================
\section{Experimental Setup}
\label{sec:setup}

\paragraph{Model.}
We use \texttt{microsoft/phi-2} (2.7B parameters,
\texttt{float16}, CUDA)~\citep{phi2} with \memeic{}'s dual LoRA
adapters (rank-16, alpha-32) and external dual memory using
\texttt{all-MiniLM-L6-v2} sentence embeddings~\citep{reimers2019sentence}.
The visual encoder is CLIP ViT-L/14-336~\citep{radford2021clip}.

\paragraph{Datasets.}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=1pt]
  \item \textbf{Train2017}: 200 COCO-derived edit triples; used for main
    \memeic{} evaluation and ablation.
  \item \textbf{Adversarial-2k}: our new 2{,}000-sample benchmark;
    used for all four diagnostic experiments.
  \item \textbf{CCKEB}: the original \memeic{} continual-compositional
    benchmark; used for SOTA comparison.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Baselines.}
We compare against: pure RAG (no parameter editing), text-only RAG,
\textsc{SERAC}, \textsc{IKE}, \textsc{WISE}, \textsc{MEND},
LoRA fine-tuning, and the \memeic{} base system (no connector).

\paragraph{Implementation details.}
All experiments run on a single NVIDIA GPU.
The sentence embedder is pinned to CPU to avoid CUDA memory fragmentation;
retrieval uses efficient NumPy matrix multiplication.
Checkpoints are saved every 100 samples and experiments are fully
reproducible via the released code.

