\noindent\textbf{Key findings.}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=2pt]
  \item \textbf{Cross-modal conflict} is the hardest category (0.8\%
    baseline), and only improves to 10.5\% with the no-connector variant,
    suggesting that the connector actually \emph{hurts} conflict resolution
    by blending conflicting signals.
  \item \textbf{Hard-visual} samples benefit most from the no-connector
    variant (+12.0\pp), indicating that visual-only retrieval is preferable
    when the textual context is adversarially crafted.
  \item \textbf{Gated connector (Exp3)} delivers the largest overall gain:
    \improve{+3.45\pp} edit, \improve{+7.60\pp} rephrase over no-connector.
  \item \textbf{Adaptive gating (Exp1)} slightly hurts performance
    ($-0.55\pp$), suggesting that a simple rule-based gating heuristic
    introduces noise on adversarial inputs.
  \item \textbf{Soft top-k (Exp2)} is nearly neutral (+0.05\pp), offering
    no adversarial advantage over hard-max retrieval.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Diagnostic Experiments Detail}
\label{sec:diag}

Figure~\ref{fig:adv2k_exps} summarises all four diagnostic experiments on
Adversarial-2k.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figs/fig3_adv2k_experiments.png}
  \caption{Adversarial-2k diagnostic results (N=2,000).  Each panel shows
  edit accuracy (blue) and rephrase accuracy (red, hatched) for one repair
  strategy.  The gated connector (Exp3, panel 3) yields the largest
  consistent improvement.}
  \label{fig:adv2k_exps}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Exp1: Adaptive modality gating.}
Despite detecting conflicts in 95.5\% of samples (1,910 / 2,000), the
adaptive alpha reduction from 0.9 to 0.5 consistently degrades accuracy
by $-0.55\pp$ (edit) and $-0.50\pp$ (rephrase).  The negative result
suggests that blunt alpha reduction is insufficient---a learned gating
mechanism is needed.

\paragraph{Exp2: Soft top-k retrieval.}
The soft interpolation over $k=5$ neighbours yields a negligible +0.05\pp
improvement.  The extremely small retrieval margins observed (mean
$\sim$0.006 cosine distance) suggest the Adversarial-2k queries are
deliberately constructed to fall near decision boundaries, rendering
soft top-k no more effective than hard max.

\paragraph{Exp3: Gated connector.}
Selective connector activation provides the most substantial improvement:
+3.45\pp{} edit accuracy and +7.60\pp{} rephrase accuracy.  The gain is
concentrated on polysemy (+2.39\pp) and near-miss (+4.35\pp) categories,
confirming that selective fusion helps when ambiguity is semantic rather
than purely visual.

\paragraph{Exp4: Confidence-based deferral.}
The always-accept baseline achieves the highest raw edit accuracy at
\best{59.80\,\%} and rephrase 47.20\,\%---but at the cost of accepting
\emph{every} sample, including highly uncertain ones.  Imposing a
confidence threshold $\tau_c$ dramatically changes the coverage--accuracy
trade-off: at all three threshold values ($\tau_c \in \{0.5, 0.6, 0.7\}$),
the system \emph{rejects} exactly \textbf{1{,}009 / 2{,}000 samples}
(50.45\,\% rejection rate), yielding edit accuracy \textbf{42.10\,\%}
on the accepted subset.  This represents a $-17.7\pp$ drop vs.\
always-accept, meaning the model is \emph{more} uncertain on the samples
it defers and the accepted samples are not the easier ones.
The plateau across $\tau_c = 0.5, 0.6, 0.7$ (identical rejection set)
suggests the model's top-token probability distribution is bimodal:
samples either exceed 0.5 consistently or fall below it, leaving no
marginal cases in the $[0.5, 0.7]$ band.
\textbf{Key takeaway}: confidence deferral is ineffective as a standalone
repair strategy on adversarial inputs; the model's confidence is
miscalibrated relative to actual correctness.

\subsection{Ablation Study}
\label{sec:ablation}

Table~\ref{tab:ablation} presents the ablation of \memeic{} components on
the Train2017 benchmark.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Ablation of \memeic{} components on Train2017 (N=200).}
\label{tab:ablation}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Configuration} & \textbf{Edit Acc.} & \textbf{Rephrase} & \textbf{Portability} \\
\midrule
Full \memeic{}             & 0.710 & 0.740 & 0.140 \\
w/o Retrieval module       & 0.185 & 0.200 & 0.095 \\
w/o Connector              & 0.865 & 0.825 & 0.175 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\noindent Removing the retrieval module causes a catastrophic \degrade{-52.5\pp}
edit accuracy drop (0.710 $\to$ 0.185), confirming retrieval as the
primary enabler of successful editing.  Removing the connector
\emph{increases} raw edit accuracy (+15.5\pp) but degrades compositional
behaviour on complex queries---captured by the lower rephrase accuracy in
Table~\ref{tab:main_results}.

\subsection{Sensitivity Analysis}
\label{sec:sensitivity}

Figure~\ref{fig:sensitivity} shows that edit accuracy peaks at
$\alpha=0.9$ (0.740) and degrades sharply at $\alpha=0.1$ (0.555).
Portability is near-flat across $\alpha$ (0.135--0.145), suggesting
that portability depends more on the connector's cross-modal bridge than
on the fusion weight.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.55\linewidth]{figs/fig5_sensitivity.png}
  \caption{Sensitivity of edit accuracy (blue, left axis) and portability
  (red dashed, right axis) to the fusion weight $\alpha$ on Train2017.}
  \label{fig:sensitivity}
\end{figure}

% ============================================================================
%  8. ANALYSIS AND DISCUSSION
% ============================================================================
\section{Analysis and Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Why does the gated connector work?}
The connector succeeds by \emph{selectively} activating cross-modal fusion.
On polysemy samples, the gate tends to fire (activate connector) because
the ambiguous visual token benefits from textual disambiguation.  On
conflict samples, the gate tends to block (bypass connector) because the
connector would otherwise blend contradictory signals.  A learned binary
gate therefore approximates an oracle that ``knows when not to fuse.''

\paragraph{The hardness of cross-modal conflict.}
Cross-modal conflict remains the most resilient failure mode (best: 10.5\%).
We attribute this to the model's pre-training: phi-2 was trained on
uncontested (image, text) pairs.  At inference time, a genuine conflict
between the visual memory entry and the textual edit activates the model's
prior---the stronger modality (usually visual) wins.  A principled
resolution requires either re-weighting the LoRA adapters per conflict
flag or introducing a dedicated conflict-resolution head.

\paragraph{Practical implications.}
Our results suggest a design principle for robust multimodal editors:
\textit{do not always fuse}.  The optimal strategy is modality-conditional:
apply fusion only when visual and textual signals are mutually consistent
and jointly necessary.  This motivates future work on
\emph{conditional fusion} policies learned from conflict-annotated data.

\paragraph{Limitations.}
(1)~The Adversarial-2k benchmark is constructed using \texttt{phi-2} as
the probe model; adversarial properties may differ for larger models
(\eg, LLaVA-13B, GPT-4V).
(2)~Portability remains low ($\leq$0.05 on Adversarial-2k) across all
methods, indicating that cross-modal compositional reasoning is not yet
solved by retrieval augmentation alone.
(3)~Exp4 (confidence deferral) is a partial solution: it improves per-sample
accuracy but reduces coverage, introducing a recall penalty.

% ============================================================================
%  9. CONCLUSION
% ============================================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We introduced \adcmf{}, a diagnostic framework for cross-modal composition
failures in retrieval-augmented multimodal knowledge editing.  Our analysis
of 195 failure cases identified five systematic failure modes and motivated
the Adversarial-2k benchmark.  Among four targeted repair strategies, the
gated cross-modal connector delivers the most consistent improvement
(+3.45\pp{} edit, +7.60\pp{} rephrase).  Critically, adaptive modality
gating and soft top-k retrieval yield near-zero or negative effects on
adversarial inputs, challenging the common assumption that more flexible
retrieval is universally beneficial.  We release all code, datasets,
and checkpoints to support reproducibility and future work.

\paragraph{Broader impact.}
Reliable multimodal knowledge editing is essential for keeping AI systems
aligned with rapidly evolving factual knowledge.  Our failure taxonomy and
benchmark are intended to surface risks (particularly cross-modal conflicts)
\emph{before} deployment.  We do not foresee misuse beyond standard
risks of large pre-trained model research.

