\subsection{Failure Analysis: Confidence vs.\ Correctness}

Figure~\ref{fig:confidence_analysis} reveals an important pattern: \memeic{} is often confident in its incorrect predictions, suggesting that the model's high confidence does not correlate with accuracy on challenging cross-modal reasoning tasks.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{figs/visual_confidence_vs_failure.png}
  \caption{Confidence versus correctness scatter plot. Many failures occur with high model confidence, indicating the model is overconfident in incorrect predictions on cross-modal composition tasks.}
  \label{fig:confidence_analysis}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Category-wise Failure Breakdown}

Figure~\ref{fig:failure_categories} shows that conflict-related failures (where visual and textual information contradict) remain the most challenging, with the lowest correction rate across all approaches.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figs/visual_failure_categories.png}
